  "response": "## Verdict: request changes, don't block\n\nThe finding is `crime_00021`, severity **low** (confidence 0.95). Evidence: **byte size: 260,000 bytes (253.9 KB)** — only just over the 200 KB low threshold, well below medium (500 KB) or high (1000 KB). One image at 254 KB on a hero is fixable, not shippable-as-is but not a merge-blocker either. Comment with required changes, approve once they land.\n\n## Recommended transformation\n\n**Target render area.** A standard full-bleed landing hero renders around 1440–1600 px wide × 600–720 px tall on desktop. Ship two source widths and let `srcset` pick: ~1600 px (1x desktop) and ~3200 px (2x retina). Anything beyond 3200 px wide is wasted bytes — phones and tablets get smaller `srcset` entries (e.g. 768 / 1200). At 254 KB the current PNG is almost certainly oversized in *pixel* dimensions, not just in encoding — resizing first usually does more work than re-encoding.\n\n**Format: AVIF, with a WebP fallback in `<picture>`.** For a hero specifically:\n\n- **AVIF** typically lands 30–50% smaller than WebP at matched perceptual quality, and hero LCP is the page's most expensive paint — every KB shaved goes straight to Core Web Vitals.\n- Browser support in 2026 is broad enough to make AVIF the primary (Safari 16+, Chrome, Firefox, Edge). The fallback is a one-line `<source type=\"image/webp\">` for the long tail.\n- WebP-only would be the call if encode time were a constraint (build pipeline, on-the-fly resizing) — for a static hero re-encoded once at build, AVIF's slower encode doesn't matter.\n\nRealistic target after both passes: **<60 KB for the 1x AVIF, <120 KB for the 2x.** If they can't hit that, the source dimensions are still too large.",
